│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The transformation in aggressive-instcombine folds two consecutive i8 loads   │
│ and an or/shift into a single i16 load with zext. In the reproducer, the      │
│ original IR uses 64-bit GEP indices (i64) with a datalayout specifying 64-bit │
│ pointer index size (e-n64). The transformed IR emits a GEP using an i32 index │
│ with a large negative value. This truncation/wrap of the offset results in a  │
│ pointer outside the allocated block, and the subsequent load triggers UB as   │
│ shown by Alive2.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The source uses getelementptr inbounds nuw i8, ptr %data, i64 ... (64-bit   │
│ indices).                                                                     │
│ - The target transformation uses getelementptr i8, ptr %data, i32 -2145291720 │
│ (note i32 index and negative value).                                          │
│ - Alive2 demonstrates that the target computes a pointer with a negative      │
│ offset and triggers UB on load, while the source remains poison-only, hence   │
│ “Source is more defined than target”.                                         │
│ - The debug-only log shows the foldConsecutiveLoads produced: %#0 = gep ptr   │
│ %data, 1 x i32 2149675576, which is consistent with truncation to 32-bit.     │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In AggressiveInstCombine.cpp within foldConsecutiveLoads, when reconstructing │
│ the base pointer for the wider load, the code calls Builder.CreatePtrAdd with │
│ a constant created via Builder.getInt32(Offset1.getZExtValue()). This         │
│ hardcodes the index type to i32 regardless of the module’s pointer index      │
│ size. Under a datalayout with 64-bit indices (e-n64), large offsets cannot be │
│ represented in 32-bit and wrap to negative, producing incorrect addressing    │
│ and UB.                                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ Specifically:                                                                 │
│ - At lines 802–808, after stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets, the code does:   │
│   Load1Ptr = Builder.CreatePtrAdd(Load1Ptr,                                   │
│ Builder.getInt32(Offset1.getZExtValue()));                                    │
│ - This should instead use the correct index type derived from the DataLayout  │
│ for the pointer operand, e.g., DL.getIndexType(Load1Ptr->getType()), and      │
│ create a ConstantInt of that type with the APInt Offset1 without truncation.  │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - File: llvm/lib/Transforms/AggressiveInstCombine/AggressiveInstCombine.cpp   │
│ - Lines: 802–808                                                              │
│ - Change the creation of the index constant for PtrAdd to use the DL-derived  │
│ index type instead of hardcoded i32.                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ Suggested replacement for those lines:                                        │
│                                                                               │
│   // Use the correct DL-based index type for pointer arithmetic.              │
│   APInt Offset1(DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(Load1Ptr->getType()), 0);           │
│   Load1Ptr = Load1Ptr->stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets(                     │
│       DL, Offset1, /* AllowNonInbounds */ true);                              │
│   Type *IdxTy = DL.getIndexType(Load1Ptr->getType());                         │
│   ConstantInt *IdxC = ConstantInt::get(IdxTy, Offset1);                       │
│   Load1Ptr = Builder.CreatePtrAdd(Load1Ptr, IdxC);                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Notes:                                                                        │
│ - Keep using stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets as-is, but construct the       │
│ ConstantInt using the APInt Offset1 directly to preserve width.               │
│ - DL.getIndexType returns an integer type matching the pointer’s indexing     │
│ width (respecting datalayout like e-n64).                                     │
│ - Avoid Builder.getInt32 here; using i32 caused truncation and incorrect      │
│ negative index.                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ If CreatePtrAdd requires the index to match the platform’s pointer index      │
│ type, using DL.getIndexType is the correct approach. This mirrors how other   │
│ parts of LLVM derive GEP index widths.                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The bug is due to using a hardcoded i32 constant for pointer arithmetic in    │
│ foldConsecutiveLoads under a 64-bit index datalayout, leading to offset       │
│ truncation and UB. Switching to the DL-derived index type fixes the           │
│ transformation by preserving the full offset width, producing a correct GEP   │
│ and preventing UB. This change aligns the pass with the datalayout and should │
│ resolve the Alive2 failure and any similar miscompiles under non-32-bit index │
│ configurations.                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
