  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe transformation in
aggressive-instcombine folds two consecutive i8 loads and an or/shift into a
single i16 load with zext. In the reproducer, the original IR uses 64-bit GEP
indices (i64) with a datalayout specifying 64-bit pointer index size (e-n64). The
transformed IR emits a GEP using an i32 index with a large negative value. This
truncation/wrap of the offset results in a pointer outside the allocated block,
and the subsequent load triggers UB as shown by Alive2.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's
Log:\n- The source uses getelementptr inbounds nuw i8, ptr %data, i64 ... (64-bit
indices).\n- The target transformation uses getelementptr i8, ptr %data, i32
-2145291720 (note i32 index and negative value).\n- Alive2 demonstrates that the
target computes a pointer with a negative offset and triggers UB on load, while
the source remains poison-only, hence \u201cSource is more defined than
target\u201d.\n- The debug-only log shows the foldConsecutiveLoads produced: %#0
= gep ptr %data, 1 x i32 2149675576, which is consistent with truncation to
32-bit.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn AggressiveInstCombine.cpp within
foldConsecutiveLoads, when reconstructing the base pointer for the wider load,
the code calls Builder.CreatePtrAdd with a constant created via
Builder.getInt32(Offset1.getZExtValue()). This hardcodes the index type to i32
regardless of the module\u2019s pointer index size. Under a datalayout with
64-bit indices (e-n64), large offsets cannot be represented in 32-bit and wrap to
negative, producing incorrect addressing and UB.\n\nSpecifically:\n- At lines
802\u2013808, after stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets, the code does:\n  Load1Ptr
= Builder.CreatePtrAdd(Load1Ptr, Builder.getInt32(Offset1.getZExtValue()));\n-
This should instead use the correct index type derived from the DataLayout for
the pointer operand, e.g., DL.getIndexType(Load1Ptr->getType()), and create a
ConstantInt of that type with the APInt Offset1 without truncation.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- File:
llvm/lib/Transforms/AggressiveInstCombine/AggressiveInstCombine.cpp\n- Lines:
802\u2013808\n- Change the creation of the index constant for PtrAdd to use the
DL-derived index type instead of hardcoded i32.\n\nSuggested replacement for
those lines:\n\n  // Use the correct DL-based index type for pointer
arithmetic.\n  APInt Offset1(DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(Load1Ptr->getType()),
0);\n  Load1Ptr = Load1Ptr->stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets(\n      DL,
Offset1, /* AllowNonInbounds */ true);\n  Type *IdxTy =
DL.getIndexType(Load1Ptr->getType());\n  ConstantInt *IdxC =
ConstantInt::get(IdxTy, Offset1);\n  Load1Ptr = Builder.CreatePtrAdd(Load1Ptr,
IdxC);\n\nNotes:\n- Keep using stripAndAccumulateConstantOffsets as-is, but
construct the ConstantInt using the APInt Offset1 directly to preserve width.\n-
DL.getIndexType returns an integer type matching the pointer\u2019s indexing
width (respecting datalayout like e-n64).\n- Avoid Builder.getInt32 here; using
i32 caused truncation and incorrect negative index.\n\nIf CreatePtrAdd requires
the index to match the platform\u2019s pointer index type, using DL.getIndexType
is the correct approach. This mirrors how other parts of LLVM derive GEP index
widths.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe bug is due to using a hardcoded i32 constant for
pointer arithmetic in foldConsecutiveLoads under a 64-bit index datalayout,
leading to offset truncation and UB. Switching to the DL-derived index type fixes
the transformation by preserving the full offset width, producing a correct GEP
and preventing UB. This change aligns the pass with the datalayout and should
resolve the Alive2 failure and any similar miscompiles under non-32-bit index
configurations.",
